00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:21.990
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: Good
evening and welcome.

00:00:21.990 --> 00:00:26.950 position:56%
Tonight's lecture by Haden Herrera,
Listening to Stone: The Art and Life

00:00:26.950 --> 00:00:31.900 position:56%
of Isamu Noguchi, is the kickoff
event for our exciting Martha Graham

00:00:31.900 --> 00:00:34.980
at the Library Festival,
a 10-day celebration

00:00:34.980 --> 00:00:37.550
of dance, music and design.

00:00:37.550 --> 00:00:40.350
And I know that many of you
are already planning to come

00:00:40.350 --> 00:00:43.030
to quite a few of our
upcoming events.

00:00:43.030 --> 00:00:45.740 position:56%
We are very, very pleased to be able

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:49.280
to mount three historic works
commissioned by the library

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:53.340 position:56%
from Martha Graham, including the
ballet Appalachian Spring with music

00:00:53.340 --> 00:00:57.560
by Aaron Copeland, which has
become an icon of American culture.

00:00:57.560 --> 00:01:02.570
Also Cave of the Heart with Samuel
